The paper deals with the information-theoretic analysis of cognitive radio networks, which involves the use of wireless communication techniques to opportunistically access underutilized spectrum bands. This falls under the purview of information theory (cs.IT) and networked systems (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of multi-antennas at the secondary transmitter to balance between spatial multiplexing and interference avoidance, which is a topic of interest in the field of signal processing (cs.SY) and multimedia (cs.MM). Finally, the paper deals with the issue of interference management in cognitive radio networks, which is a key challenge in the field of cognitive radio (cs.CR).
